# Summary
This lesson covers advanced pointer interactions in singly linked lists: detecting cycle structures in linear time with constant space and merging sorted list sequences in-place.

## Cycle Detection (Floyd's Algorithm)
In a linked list containing a cycle structure, simple traversals run into infinite loops. We need an algorithm to identify cycles without storing visited nodes in a hash set.
* Floyd's Cycle-Finding Algorithm uses two pointers:
  - **Slow Pointer (`tortoise`)**: Moves one node at a time.
  - **Fast Pointer (`hare`)**: Moves two nodes at a time.

$$\text{If a loop exists, the fast pointer will eventually catch up to the slow pointer: } \text{slow} == \text{fast}$$

### Code Blueprint
```javascript
function hasCycle(head) {
  if (head === null || head.next === null) {
    return false;
  }
  let slow = head;
  let fast = head;

  while (fast !== null && fast.next !== null) {
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;

    if (slow === fast) {
      return true; // Cycle detected
    }
  }
  return false; // Reached end, no cycle
}
```

